summary: Keir Starmer, the new UK Prime Minister, has declared the government's controversial Rwanda deportation plan "dead and buried." The policy, which aimed to send asylum seekers to Rwanda for processing, has faced widespread criticism and legal challenges. The government has spent over £320 million on the policy, which is expected to be lost if the Conservative Party loses the upcoming election. Starmer's announcement has been met with mixed reactions, with some welcoming the end of the plan and others raising concerns about the UK's asylum system.
